\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. T. distichum} (L.) L.C.M. Richard,{\i  Ann. Mus. Hist. Nat.} ({\i Paris}) {\b 16:} 298 (1810). Tree up to 50 m, with a rather narrow outline, often with conspicuous buttresses at the base of the trunk. Bark reddish-brown, fibrous, peeling. Leaves up to 20 mm, acute, channelled above. Male cones purplish, in slender panicles. Female cone 15-30 mm in diameter; some of the scales sterile, others bearing 2 irregularly trigonous seeds.{\i  Planted for timber in S. and S.C. Europe, especialy on alluvial land}. [Bu Ga Ge It Rm.] ({\i S.E. United States}.)
